** Registers & Kill ring (yanking)

Vim uses registers & Emacs uses a register, kill ring, buffers & markers

Registers = Save yanked text to a named register (i.e. a, 2, :, etc...)
Kill ring = Save yanked text in the order it was 'killed'

Both types, when Emacs is restarted the lists are lost/emptied

*Register shortcuts*

| Syntax    | Explanation           |
|           |                       |
| " + a + y | Yank into register a  |
| " + A + y | Append to register a  |
| " + a + p | Paste from register a |

These are specifically Vim shortcuts, but are saving the yanked text to Emacs registers

*Kill ring*

Emacs clipboard history which stores recent copied & deleted text
Compared to Vim registers, which are a named container of copied & deleted text

- Explained
If I cut "hello"
The kill ring: [ "hello" ]
Then I cut "world"
The kill ring now: [ "world", "hello" ]

*Kill ring shortcuts*

M-y (shortcut for the command consult-yank-pop) accesses the kill ring
You can type to search or the arrow keys to selected previously 'killed' text

Vim yank & cut shortcuts (i.e. yy or dd) will begin placing items in the kill ring
Then, the below is how you paste items from the kill ring

| Syntax      | Explanation                              | Comment                                              |
|             |                                          |                                                      |
| M-y         | Pull up kill ring options in mini-buffer | This works with Consult package (a Consult function) |
|             |                                          |                                                      |
| C-y         | Paste                                    |                                                      |
| M-y (again) | Paste next item in kill ring             |                                                      |


*Summary*

- Use kill ring for history
- Use registers for saving specific snippets of text 

